# Internationalization (i18n) & Localization (l10n)

**Capability test:** Agents skip this file until the project enables multiple locales. When single-locale is documented, literals on new UI are OK; use keys when i18n is planned.

Coding patterns for apps that support multiple languages/regions. IF your project needs i18n, apply these patterns. Starting early is easier than retrofitting.

All numeric values in this file are [DEFAULT] - adjust per project.

---

## The Golden Rule

**Never hardcode user-facing strings in source code.** Every string the user sees - labels, buttons, inline copy, errors, placeholders - lives in a translation file, not inline in the component.

---

## Architecture

```
Source code          Translation files          Runtime
  │                      │                        │
  │  t("greeting") ──>  en.json: "Hello"    ──>  "Hello"
  │                      ar.json: "أهلاً"    ──>  "أهلاً"
  │                      es.json: "Bienvenido"──> "Bienvenido"
```

### Translation File Structure

```
locales/
├── en/
│   ├── common.json        # Shared strings (buttons, labels, navigation)
│   ├── feature-a.json      # Feature A strings
│   ├── feature-b.json      # Feature B strings
│   ├── errors.json         # User-visible fault text
│   └── validation.json     # Form validation copy
├── ar/
│   ├── common.json
│   ├── auth.json
│   └── ...
└── es/
    ├── common.json
    └── ...
```

**Rules:**
- One JSON file per feature/domain (don't dump everything in one file)
- Keys are descriptive, dot-namespaced: `auth.entry.title`, `common.buttons.save`, `errors.notFound`
- Pick one source/default language per project (English is the most common default, but use whatever fits your primary market)
- Translation files are version-controlled (committed to git)
- Never auto-translate for production - use professional translators or verified AI translation with human review

---

## String Rules

### Never Hardcode

```
BANNED:
  <button>Save Changes</button>
  <h1>Example Page Title</h1>
  toast("Record created successfully");
  return { error: "This field is required." };

REQUIRED:
  <button>{t("common.buttons.save")}</button>
  <h1>{t("common.pageTitle")}</h1>
  toast(t("resources.created"));
  return { error: t("validation.fieldRequired") };
```

### Never Concatenate Strings

```
BANNED:
  t("hello") + " " + userName + ", " + t("youHave") + " " + count + " " + t("items")

REQUIRED (use interpolation):
  t("greeting", { name: userName, count: itemCount })

  // en.json: "Hello {{name}}, you have {{count}} items"
  // ar.json: "أهلاً {{name}}، لديك {{count}} عناصر"
```

Why: Sentence structure differs between languages. Arabic might put the count before the name.

### Pluralization

```
BANNED:
  `${count} item${count !== 1 ? "s" : ""}`

REQUIRED (use ICU / i18n plural rules):
  t("items.count", { count: itemCount })

  // en.json:
  {
    "items": {
      "count_zero": "No items",
      "count_one": "{{count}} item",
      "count_other": "{{count}} items"
    }
  }

  // ar.json (Arabic has 6 plural forms):
  {
    "items": {
      "count_zero": "لا عناصر",
      "count_one": "عنصر واحد",
      "count_two": "عنصران",
      "count_few": "{{count}} عناصر",
      "count_many": "{{count}} عنصراً",
      "count_other": "{{count}} عنصر"
    }
  }
```

Why: English has 2 plural forms. Arabic has 6. Russian has 3. Don't assume `singular/plural` is universal.

