## Date, Time & Number Formatting

### Never Format Manually

```
BANNED:
  `${month}/${day}/${year}`
  `${value.toFixed(2)} USD`    // IF your project handles monetary values - still use Intl, not manual concatenation
  `${hours}:${minutes} AM`

REQUIRED (use Intl API or equivalent):
  new Intl.DateTimeFormat(locale, { dateStyle: "medium" }).format(date)
  // IF your project handles monetary values:
  new Intl.NumberFormat(locale, { style: "currency", currency: "USD" }).format(amount)
  new Intl.DateTimeFormat(locale, { timeStyle: "short" }).format(date)
```

### Format Examples by Locale

```
Date: January 15, 2024
  en-US:  1/15/2024
  en-GB:  15/01/2024
  de-DE:  15.01.2024
  ja-JP:  2024/01/15
  ar-SA:  ١٥/٠١/٢٠٢٤

Number: 1,234,567.89
  en-US:  1,234,567.89
  de-DE:  1.234.567,89
  fr-FR:  1 234 567,89
  ar-SA:  ١٬٢٣٤٬٥٦٧٫٨٩

Currency (IF your project handles monetary values; skip if not applicable):
  Example input: major units 1,500.00 with USD
  en-US:  $1,500.00
  de-DE:  1.500,00 $
  ja-JP:  $1,500.00
  ar-SA:  ١٬٥٠٠٫٠٠ US$
```

### Rules

- **Always use Intl API** (built into every modern runtime) or the framework's equivalent
- **Store dates as UTC** in the database; convert to user's timezone on display
- **IF your project handles money:** store amounts as integers in the smallest currency unit (or fixed-scale decimal) to avoid floating-point errors
- **Let the locale drive the format** - never assume MM/DD/YYYY or comma-as-thousands-separator
- **Relative time** ("3 hours ago", "yesterday") must also be locale-aware

